sa]], [[Quezon City]]\n|rowspan=3|[[15th Congress of the Philippines|15th Congress]]\n|1st\n|rowspan=6|Filipino\n|0:36<ref name=throughtheyears>{{cite news|last1=Santos|first1=Reynaldo Jr.|title=Aquino's SONA speeches through the years|url=http://www.rappler.com/newsbreak/iq/64681-highlights-aquino-state-of-the-nation-address|accessdate=27 July 2015|publisher=Rappler|date=29 July 2014}}</ref>\n|Aquino was the first president to use Filipino and a language other than English at the SONA.<ref name=filipino>{{cite news|title=Which president was the first to deliver his State of the Nation Address (SONA) entirely in Filipino?|url=http://moneypolitics.pcij.org/2013/07/which-president-was-the-first-to-deliver-his-state-of-the-nation-address-sona-entirely-in-filipino/|accessdate=27 July 2015|work=Money Politics|publisher=Philippine Center for Investigative Journalism|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304214254/http://moneypolitics.pcij.org/2013/07/which-president-was-the-first-to-deliver-his-state-of-the-nation-address-sona-entirely-in-filipino/|archivedate=4 March 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n|73\n|{{start date|2011|07|25}}\n|''State of the Nation Address''\n|2nd\n|0:53<ref name=throughtheyears/>\n|\n|-\n|74\n|{{start date|2012|07|23}}\n|''Third State of the Nation Address''\n|3rd\n|1:27<ref name=throughtheyears/>\n|\n|-\n|75\n|{{start date|2013|07|22}}\n|''Fourth State of the Nation Address''\n|rowspan=3|[[16th Congress of the Philippines|16th Congress]]\n|1st\n|1:44<ref>{{cite news|last1=Cerda|first1=Jovan|title=65 important things mentioned in Aquino's fourth SONA|url=http://www.philstar.com/headlines/2013/07/22/1000971/65-important-things-mentioned-aquinos-fourth-sona|accessdate=27 July 2015|publisher=The Philippine Star|date=22 July 2013}}</ref>\n|\n|-\n|76\n|{{start date|2014|07|28}}\n|''Fifth State of the Nation Address''\n|2nd\n|1:31<ref>{{cite news|title=91 minutes, 85 rounds of applause|url=http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/624443/91-minutes-85-rounds-of-applause|accessdate=27 July 2015|publisher=Philippine Daily Inquirer|date=29 July 2014}}</ref>\n|\n|-\n|[[2015 State of the Nation Address (Philippines)|77]]\n|{{start date|2015|07|27}}\n|''[[2015 State of the Nation Address (Philippines)|Sixth State of the Nation Address]]''\n|3rd\n|2:13\n|\n|-\n|2016 DRUGS DRUGS DRUGS (Philippines)|78\n|rowspan=6 valign=top|[[File:Rodrigo Duterte June 2016.jpg|100px]]<br>[[Rodrigo Duterte]]\n|{{start date|2016|07|25}}\n|''Droga Droga Droga (Philippines)|''[[2016 State of the Nation Address (Philippines)|First State of the Nation Address]]''\n|rowspan=6|[[Batasang Pambansa]], [[Quezon City]]\n|rowspan=4|[[17th Congress of the Philippines|17th Congress]]\n|1st\n|rowspan=6|English  \n|1:33\n| \n|-\n|79\n|{{start date|2017|07|24}}\n|''Second State of the Nation Address''\n|2nd\n|2:00\n|\n|-\n|80\n|{{start date|2018|07|23}}\n|''[[2018 State of the Nation Address (Philippines)|Third State of the Nation Address]]''\n|3rd\n|0:48\n|\n|-\n|81\n|{{start date|2019|07|22}}\n|''[[2019 State of the Nation Address (Philippines)|Fourth State of the Nation Address]]''\n|4th\n|1:33\n|\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.gov.ph/past-sona-speeches/ State of the Nation Addresses - Official Gazette of the Republic of the Philippines]\n{{State of the Nation Address}}\n\n[[Category:State of the Nation Address (Philippines)|*]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:2011 Philippine State of the Nation Address.jpg|thumb|right|300px|President [[Benigno Aquino III]] delivers his second State of the Nation Address at the Plenary Hall of the [[Batasang Pambansa Complex]] on July 25, 2011.]]\n\nSeventy-nine annual [[State of the Nation Address (Philippines)|State of the Nation Addresses]] (SONA) have been delivered since 1935 by thirteen presidents of the [[Philippines]].\n\n==History==\nPrior to the introduction of the SONA, similar speeches were given by Philippine presidents. The precursor of the SONA was the State of the Katipunan Address held in March 22, 1897 by [[Andres Bonifacio]], who is considered by some to be the first president of the Philippines. Emilio Aguinaldo, officially recognized as the first president of the Philippines, held a State of the Revolutionary Nation Address in September 15, 1898 after opening the [[Revolutionary Government of the Philippines|Malolos Congress]] entitled ''Mensaje Leido por el Presidente del Govierno Revolucionario para el Congreso''. On June 16, 1936, [[Manuel L. Quezon]] held a State of the Commonwealth Government Affairs at the inaugural session of the National Assembly.<ref name=\"fast facts\">{{cite news|title=Fast facts about the Sona|url=http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/inquirerheadlines/learning/view/20100725-283093/Fast-facts-about-the-Sona|accessdate=27 July 2015|publisher=Philippine Daily Inquirer|date=25 July 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe first SONA was made by [[Manuel L. Quezon]] in 1935 before the National Assembly. Among those who made a SONA, [[Ferdinand Marcos]] made twenty SONAs - the largest number made by a single president. [[Sergio Osme\u00f1a]] in contrast made just one. Among the officially recognized presidents two presidents did not make a single SONA - Emilio Aguinaldo and [[Jos\u00e9 P. Laurel]]. Marcos was the only one who did not deliver a SONA before the Congress (1973, 1974, 1975, 1976, and 1977). [[Elpidio Quirino]]'s 1950 speech was delivered through radio broadcast when he was confined at the [[Johns Hopkins Hospital]] in [[Baltimore]], [[Maryland]] in the [[United States]].<ref name=cnnph>{{cite news|last1=Ansis|first1=JC|title=What you need to know about SONAs|url=http://cnnphilippines.com/news/2015/07/23/state-of-the-nation-address-sona-what-you-need-to-know.html|accessdate=27 July 2015|publisher=CNN Philippines|date=25 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe SONA is traditionally held annually. The presidential speech has been delivered in English until 2009 when it was last delivered in the said language.{{citation needed|date=July 2015}} Benigno Aquino III was the first president to deliver the presidential speech in [[Filipino language|Filipino]]. He used Filipino in all of his six speeches from 2010 to 2015.\n\nThe longest speech was made by [[Ferdinand Marcos]] in 1969, with a total of 29,335 words. In contrast, Gloria Macapagal-Arroyo's speech made in 2005 was the shortest, with only 1,551 words.<ref name=\"cnnph\"/>\n\n==List of State of the Nation addresses==\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:5%;\" |No.\n! style=\"width:10%;\" |President\n! Date\n! Title\n! Venue\n! Legislature\n! Session\n! Language\n! Duration<br><small>hours and minutes</small>\n! Notes\n|-\n|1\n|rowspan=7 valign=top|[[File:Manuel L. Quezon (November 1942).jpg|100px]]<br>[[Manuel L. Quezon]]\n|{{start date|1935|11|25}}\n|''Message to the First Assembly on National Defense''\n|rowspan=7|Legislative Building, [[Manila]]\n|rowspan=4|[[1st Philippine Legislature|1st National Assembly]]\n|rowspan=2|1st\n|rowspan=7|English\n|\n|\n|-\n|2\n|{{start date|1936|06|16}}\n|''On the Country\u2019s Conditions and Problems''\n|\n|\n|-\n|3\n|{{start date|1937|10|18}}\n|''Improvement of Philippine Conditions, Philippine Independence, and Relations with American High Commissioner''\n|2nd\n|\n|\n|-\n|4\n|{{start date|1938|01|24}}\n|''Revision of the System of Taxation''\n|3rd\n|\n|\n|-\n|5\n|{{start date|1939|01|24}}\n|''The State of the Nation and Important Economic Problems''\n|rowspan=3|[[2nd Philippine Legislature|2nd National Assembly]]\n|1st\n|\n|\n|-\n|6\n|{{start date|1940|01|22}}\n|''The State of the Nation''\n|2nd\n|\n|\n|-\n|7\n|{{start date|1941|01|31}}\n|''The State of the Nation''\n|3rd\n|\n|\n|-\n|8\n| valign=top|[[File:Osmena.jpg|100px]]<br>[[Sergio Osme\u00f1a]]\n|{{start date|1945|06|09}}\n|''Message to the First Congress of the Commonwealth of Philippines''\n|rowspan=4|Lepanto Street, [[Manila]]\n|[[1st Commonwealth Congress|1st Congress of the Commonwealth]]\n|rowspan=2 {{NA}}\n|English\n|\n|\n|-\n|9\n|rowspan=3 valign=top|[[File:Manuel A Roxas.jpg|100px]]<br>[[Manuel Roxas]]\n|{{start date|1946|06|03}}\n|''The State of the Nation''\n|[[1st Commonwealth Congress|2nd Congress of the Commonwealth]]\n|rowspan=3|English\n|\n|\n|-\n|10\n|{{start date|1947|01|27}}\n|''Message on the State of the Nation''\n|rowspan=3|[[1st Congress of the Philippines|1st Congress]]\n|1st\n|\n|\n|-\n|11\n|{{start date|1948|01|26}}\n|''The Nation on the Road to Prosperity''\n|2nd\n|\n|\n|-\n|12\n|rowspan=5 valign=top|[[File:Elpidio R Quirino.jpg|100px]]<br>[[Elpidio Quirino]]\n|{{start date|1949|01|24}}\n|''The Most Urgent Aim of the Administration''\n|Legislative Building, [[Manila]]\n|3rd\n|rowspan=5|English\n|\n|\n|-\n|13\n|{{start date|1950|01|23}}\n|''Address on the State of the Nation''\n|[[Baltimore]], [[Maryland]]<br>[[United States]]\n|rowspan=4|[[2nd Congress of the Philippines|2nd Congress]]\n|1st\n|\n|delivered via radio broadcast\n|-\n|14\n|{{start date|1951|01|23}}\n|''The State of the Nation''\n|rowspan=3|Legislative Building, Manila\n|2nd\n|\n|\n|-\n|15\n|{{start date|1952|01|28}}\n|''The State of the Nation''\n|3rd\n|\n|\n|-\n|16\n|{{start date|1953|01|26}}\n|''The State of the Nation''\n|4th\n|\n|\n|-\n|17\n|rowspan=4 valign=top|[[File:Ramon F Magsaysay.jpg|100px]]<br>[[Ramon Magsaysay]]\n|{{start date|1954|01|25}}\n|''Address on the State of the Nation''\n|rowspan=4|Legislative Building, [[Manila]]\n|rowspan=4|[[3rd Congress of the Philippines|3rd Congress]]\n|1st\n|rowspan=4|English\n|\n|\n|-\n|18\n|{{start date|1955|01|24}}\n|''Address on the State of the Nation''\n|2nd\n|\n|\n|-\n|19\n|{{start date|1956|01|23}}\n|''Address on the State of the Nation''\n|3rd\n|\n|\n|-\n|20\n|{{start date|1957|01|28}}\n|''Address on the State of the Nation''\n|4th\n|\n|\n|-\n|21\n|rowspan=4 valign=top|[[File:Carlos P Garcia.jpg|100px]]<br>[[Carlos P. Garcia]]\n|{{start date|1958|01|27}}\n|''Address on the State of the Nation''\n|rowspan=4|Legislative Building, [[Manila]]\n|rowspan=4|[[4th Congress o